data.name: txtThreshold.HelpString
data.value: GBMM analyzes the DEM to create a flow path grid; cell in this grid are considered "streams", and all other cells are "overland". The flow path will be defined downstream of all accumulated flow areas which exceed the stream area threshold you enter here.

data.name: lnkMergeCatchments.HelpString
data.value: Click this link to open a form which allows you to select subcatchment shapes (such as those found in the NHD Catchments layer) and combine them into a single subbasin shape. This shape is added to your existing subbasin layer indicated above; if a new subbasin layer is selected, it will be created.

data.name: txtInputName.HelpString
data.value: Specify the name of the folder where input to the GBMM C++ computational program will be placed; note that the GBMM input file (specified by clicking the Save As... button) must also reside in this folder. This path would normally look like: C:\Basins\data\01234567\GBMM\

data.name: chkForceRebuild.HelpString
data.value: Normally, input grids are rebuild only when their source grids have been updated (by comparing file dates). In some cases you may need to override this behaviour and force the files to be rebuilt (such as when you change source files outside the preprocessor).

data.name: chkAddLayers.HelpString
data.value: This controls whether temporary working grids created by GBMM will be automatically added to your current map. If you uncheck this and later want to add selected layers, they can be found in the TEMP folder, parallel to the INPUT folder specified on the General tab.

data.name: Label7.Text
data.value:
The Mercury tab is where you specify the initial mercury concentration in watershed soil and mercury deposition fluxes from atmosphere.
Separate mercury accumulation factors are entered for land, forest, water, and benthic sediments.

data.name: Label2.Text
data.value: The Hydrology tab is used to specify overland and groundwater hydrologic parameters for runoff and water balance calculations, stream hydraulics parameters for travel time calculations, and lake hydraulics information.

data.name: Label1.Text
data.value:
The Grid-Based Mercury Model (GBMM) calculates mercury load from direct deposition, runoff, erosion, and point sources based on EPA's IEM-2M watershed module. This General tab is used to specify input data, interface loads, GIS data layers, lookup tables, and stream and lake information.
You can only select previously loaded MapWindow layers from those types presented in the drop-down lists; many GIS shape (feature) layers allow you to also specify the ID field that links to the appropriate data tables. All data tables must be in .txt (tab-delimited) or .dbf (dBase) formats and must contain specific fields (see documentation).

data.name: Label59.Text
data.value: An important transport mechanism for mercury is via erosion and sediment transport. The Sediment tab allows you to enter parameters associated with the Universal Soil Loss Equation (USLE) to predict erosion and sediment transport. These parameters apply to both overland and lake routing.
